<br>
It's pretty obvious that the guild is going through some rough times; some saw it coming, some didn't. I bow before those in the guild that chose to stay and work to fix the problems, rather than leave.<br>
<br>
I suggested as one of the first steps that the officers get in touch with those of us who left the guild (recently or a while ago, it doesn't matter) and get their input. Some left without a word, some said a nice goodbye, very few gave us a thing or two to think about.<br>
<br>
Temp listed the main issues that surfaced lately.<br>
<br>
Guild growth: I'm one who believes in letting the guild grow naturally, but, if the decision is made to halt recruiting for a while, I will respect that decision. I want however to point out that I only know of ONE person who left because of this: Hworang; there could be more, but I don't know that. I am not trying to dismiss the issue, I'm only saying let's not make it into more than it is.  I suggested an open poll, where the whole guild can speak up on this. Afterall, it's everyone's guild...<br>
<br>
Personal issues: I think that's the #1 reason people leave DoK, or any guild for that matter. It's human nature to disagree and we can't prevent that. What we can do is be more careful in how we communicate with each other, so that disagreements don't turn into arguments and hurt feelings.<br>
It doesn't matter that I think Col was right in most of his assessments; it doesn't matter that I'd take guys who speak their minds (like Shaedon or Kikulle) over someone hidding around the bushes. Some people don't respond well to being pushed and we should understand that, if we want to stay a group and not a military faction.  I'm sure those involved got a message and they'll think about it.  Good things will come out of this mess in the end.<br>
<br>
